    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>In 2024, a team of researchers at the University of New Mexico published a paper that quietly rewrote the terms of the microplastics conversation. They weren't studying fish. They weren't studying water or soil or Arctic ice cores. They were studying human brains.</p>

      <p>What they found was that brain tissue from autopsy samples contained, on average, about 4,800 micrograms of plastic per gram of tissue — the equivalent, by weight, of a plastic spoon distributed across the brain. Samples from 2024 contained roughly 50% more plastic than samples from 2016. And brains from people who had been diagnosed with dementia before death contained significantly higher concentrations than those who hadn't.</p>

      <p>That last finding has not been established as causal. The researchers were careful to say so. But the correlation was robust enough, and the mechanism plausible enough, that "preliminary" is doing some heavy lifting in describing where this science now stands.</p>

      <p>Microplastics are no longer an environmental problem that happens to affect humans incidentally. They are a human health problem with an environmental origin — and the exposure is, at this point, essentially universal.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="how-they-get-in" class="reveal">
      <h2>How They Get In</h2>

      <p>Microplastics are defined as plastic particles smaller than 5 millimeters. Nanoplastics are a subset: fragments smaller than a micrometer, some measured in nanometers. The distinction matters because size determines biological behavior. Larger microplastics tend to accumulate in the gut and are largely excreted. Nanoplastics are small enough to cross cell membranes, translocate into the bloodstream, and deposit in organs.</p>

      <p>The sources are extensive to the point of being difficult to enumerate. They include:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Food and water.</strong> Plastic packaging continuously sheds particles into its contents, particularly under heat. A single plastic water bottle can release millions of nanoplastic particles per liter. Seafood accumulates microplastics throughout the marine food chain. Tap water contains them in most cities that have been tested.</li>
        <li><strong>Air.</strong> Synthetic fabrics shed plastic microfibers with every wash cycle; those fibers enter household dust and are inhaled. Outdoor air, particularly in urban environments, carries plastic particles from tire wear, industrial emissions, and degrading waste.</li>
        <li><strong>Food preparation.</strong> Cutting on plastic cutting boards generates fragments. Heating food in plastic containers dramatically accelerates leaching. Scratched non-stick pans shed fluoropolymers with every use.</li>
        <li><strong>Salt and soil.</strong> Sea salt is one of the most contaminated food sources. Agricultural soils treated with sewage sludge contain high concentrations of microplastics that enter crops.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The estimated human ingestion rate is staggering. Studies vary, but the median estimates suggest adults consume somewhere between 74,000 and 121,000 microplastic particles per year through diet alone — more if they drink bottled water. Inhalation adds substantially to that figure. A 2019 study estimated that people who drink predominantly bottled water consume approximately 90,000 additional particles annually compared to those who drink tap water.</p>

      <p>We are not talking about trace exposures.</p>
    </section>

