    <section id="where-they-end-up" class="reveal">
      <h2>Where They End Up</h2>

      <p>The original assumption was that microplastics were largely inert — that they passed through the digestive system without meaningful absorption and were excreted without consequence. That assumption has not survived contact with the research.</p>

      <p>Microplastics have now been detected in:</p>

      <ul>
        <li>Human blood (2022, a peer-reviewed first)</li>
        <li>The placenta — including fetal-side tissue</li>
        <li>Breast milk</li>
        <li>Lung tissue</li>
        <li>Testicular tissue</li>
        <li>Cardiac tissue, including inside arterial plaques</li>
        <li>Liver, kidney, and spleen</li>
        <li>And, as noted, the brain</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The presence of microplastics in arterial plaques generated significant clinical attention in 2024, when a study published in the <em>New England Journal of Medicine</em> found that patients whose plaques contained detectable levels of polyethylene or polyvinyl chloride had a significantly higher risk of heart attack, stroke, and death over the subsequent three years compared to patients whose plaques were plastic-free. The study was observational and the mechanism unproven, but it was the most direct clinical evidence to date that plastic accumulation is not biologically neutral.</p>
    </section>

