    <section id="what-they-do" class="reveal">
      <h2>What They Do</h2>

      <p>The mechanisms by which microplastics cause harm are increasingly understood, and they operate through several pathways simultaneously.</p>

      <h3>Direct Physical Damage</h3>

      <p>Plastic particles, particularly angular microplastics, cause mechanical irritation to tissues. In the gut, this disrupts the mucosal lining. In lung tissue, it triggers local inflammatory responses similar to those seen with other inhaled particulates.</p>

      <h3>Chemical Leaching</h3>

      <p>Plastics are not pure polymers. They contain a range of additives — plasticizers, flame retardants, stabilizers, colorants — many of which are biologically active. Phthalates and bisphenols, both widely used in plastics, are endocrine disruptors: they interfere with hormone signaling at extremely low concentrations. BPA's replacement chemicals (BPS, BPF) appear to have similar or worse hormonal effects, despite having been marketed as safer alternatives.</p>

      <h3>Inflammatory Activation</h3>

      <p>This is where the brain story becomes particularly significant. Microplastics — especially at nanoscale — trigger innate immune responses wherever they deposit. In brain tissue, this activates microglia, the resident immune cells that, under chronic activation, become neurotoxic. The pattern of inflammation associated with microplastic exposure in preclinical models resembles early Alzheimer's and Parkinson's pathology in ways that are uncomfortable to dismiss.</p>

      <h3>Microbiome Disruption</h3>

      <p>The gut microbiome is exquisitely sensitive to its chemical environment. Microplastics alter its composition, reducing the diversity and abundance of beneficial bacteria while enriching pro-inflammatory species. Given the centrality of the gut-brain axis to mood, cognition, and systemic inflammation, this disruption has downstream effects that extend well beyond digestion.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-brain-question" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Brain Question</h2>

      <p>The New Mexico brain tissue study was not the only research pointing toward neurological consequences. A 2026 review in <em>Neuroscience News</em> summarized several lines of converging evidence:</p>

      <p>In animal models, nanoplastic exposure produces measurable cognitive deficits — reduced performance on memory and learning tasks — along with elevated markers of neuroinflammation and oxidative stress. The dose levels used in these studies are not dramatically above what humans encounter through routine exposure, which is part of what makes the literature uncomfortable to read.</p>

      <p>In human epidemiological data, associations between plastic chemical exposure (typically measured via urinary phthalate or bisphenol metabolites) and cognitive decline, ADHD symptoms in children, and neurodevelopmental delays have been reported across multiple independent cohorts.</p>

      <p>The blood-brain barrier, the structure that regulates what enters brain tissue from the bloodstream, is not impervious to nanoplastics. Studies have demonstrated that nanoparticles below 100 nanometers can cross it — and that the barrier's integrity is further compromised by the inflammatory cascade that plastic particles trigger in the cerebrovascular endothelium. It's a compounding problem: the particles weaken the barrier that was supposed to keep them out.</p>

      <p>The dementia correlation in the New Mexico brain data has not been replicated at scale. It may not hold up. But the mechanistic plausibility — neuroinflammation, oxidative stress, endocrine disruption, microbiome disruption all converging on brain tissue — is the kind of convergence that tends to predict findings that do hold up.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"The particles weaken the barrier that was supposed to keep them out."</p>
