    <section id="what-can-actually-be-done" class="reveal">
      <h2>What Can Actually Be Done</h2>

      <p>This is the section where the honest answer is uncomfortable: individual mitigation is partial at best. You cannot opt out of microplastic exposure the way you can choose not to smoke. The contamination of air, water, soil, and most food systems is systemic. At current emission rates, it will get worse before any meaningful remediation occurs.</p>

      <p>That said, the difference between median exposure and low-exposure behavior is not trivial.</p>

      <h3>Meaningful Reductions</h3>

      <ul>
        <li>Replace plastic water bottles and food storage with glass or stainless steel. The contribution of food and beverage packaging to total load is among the highest and most controllable.</li>
        <li>Avoid heating food in plastic. Migration rates increase dramatically with temperature — even containers labeled "microwave safe" shed significantly more particles when heated.</li>
        <li>Filter tap water through a quality reverse osmosis or ceramic filter. Studies have found these reduce microplastic content in water by 80–95%.</li>
        <li>Ventilate and vacuum frequently. Household dust is a significant inhalation source, and regular cleaning measurably reduces airborne particle load.</li>
        <li>Reduce ultra-processed food consumption — not only for the metabolic reasons covered elsewhere, but because heavily processed foods involve more plastic contact at higher temperatures throughout manufacturing and packaging.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Limited Value</h3>

      <ul>
        <li>Avoiding sea salt (already contaminated) — worthwhile but a minor contributor to total load.</li>
        <li>"BPA-free" labels — meaningful only if replacements are actually safer, which current evidence does not confirm.</li>
        <li>Air purifiers — help with larger airborne particles but are largely ineffective against nanoplastics.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The Systemic Lever</h3>

      <p>Individual behavior change matters at the margins. The real variable is regulatory and industrial. Extended producer responsibility legislation, microplastic filtration requirements for wastewater treatment, and restrictions on single-use plastics in food contact applications are the interventions that would actually move the needle at population level. Several European jurisdictions are further along this path than others.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="the-honest-assessment" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Honest Assessment</h2>

      <p>There is a tendency in health journalism to oscillate between two positions on emerging environmental health risks: confident alarm or confident dismissal. The microplastics story doesn't support either posture right now.</p>

      <p>What the evidence says is this: the exposures are real, universal, and increasing. Microplastics accumulate in human organs including the brain. Several mechanisms by which they cause harm are biologically plausible and supported by preclinical data. Human epidemiological associations with disease are present but not yet definitive. The time scales of these exposures are long enough that we may be studying the early stages of a health burden whose full shape won't be clear for decades.</p>

      <p>None of that is reason for panic. It is, however, reason to take the question seriously — and reason to be skeptical of anyone who tells you, with confidence, that there is nothing to worry about.</p>

      <p>The plastics industry said the same thing about PFAS for thirty years.</p>
    </section>

